&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;From 2018-2020, NSF support of this postdoctoral fellowship supported professional development of Dr. Beth K. Scaffidi, as well as the development of the Andean Paleomobility Unification (APU) Project, which Scaffidi continues to direct. The major goals of the APU project were: 1) to develop complete databases of strontium and oxygen isotope values from archaeological sites in the Andes, 2) to analyze baseline environmental materials (water, plants, and fauna) for bioavailable strontium content and develop predictive isoscapes modeling expectations of local strontium and oxygen values, 3) and to test additional archaeological materials for strontium content, in order to better define local isotopic signatures throughout southern Peru. The major accomplishment of the professionalization aspect of this fellowship was to prepare Dr. Scaffidi for a tenure-track faculty position, and to direct her new laboratory at the University of California, Merced, the Skeletal and Environmental Isotope Laboratory (SEIL).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The intellectual merits of this project include archaeological and environmental models of predicted strontium and oxygen isotope variation throughout the Andes, three peer-reviewed journal articles, two peer-reviewed book chapters, an undergraduate honors thesis, and seven conference presentations at the annual meetings of the Society for American Archaeology, the Institute of Andean Studies, and the American Association of Physical Anthropology. Scaffidi also developed several new aspects of her isotopic archaeology research through two pilot grants from the Center for Bioarchaeological Research at Arizona State University (ASU). These grants supported collaborations with students and faculty from four other universities and two public museums, and publications on these results are in progress.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Broader impacts of the research has included the mentorship of 11 undergraduate students through the School of Human Evolution and Social Change?s (SHESC) Research Apprenticeship Program in the Archaeological Chemistry Laboratory, public bioarchaeological outreach through SHESC community programs, guest lectures through ASU classes and the Osher Institute for Lifelong Education, and the supervision of an ASU student at field research sites in Peru and through the Flinn Foundation?s Internship program. The isotopic models are publicly-available for use by researchers and professionals tracking mobility in the Andes, such as conservation biologists, ecologists, and forensic scientists. Finally, focusing on understanding mobility in the past has led to Scaffidi?s involvement with the Center for Archaeological Synthesis, which strives to leverage archaeological big data to understand how humans of the past adapted to challenges and apply those findings to today?s problems. Scaffidi is currently a co-PI on two collaborative, synthetic grant proposals that examine long-term patterns of mobility, especially in response to climate-related stresses. These projects will contribute to normalizing the experience of human migration, and ultimately assist policy makers with developing policies informed by a deep-time perspective.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

